# WifiForge - Using Bettercap in WifiForge
## What's Bettercap? 

Bettercap describes itself as the swiss army knife for wireless attacks. With Bettercap, attacks can be performed against bluetooth, Wifi, and wireless HID devices. We'll be using Bettercap for reconnaissance and key cracking against a WPA2 network.
## Initialize the Environment!

Note: To get the environment, pull the WifiForge docker container from Dockerhub using the commands listed [on the project's GitHub page](https://github.com/her3ticavi/Wifi-Forge). 

```bash
python3 ./WifiForge.py
```


Once it launches, a menu should appear as pictured below. There are two options related to bettercap in the menu - Bettercap Recon and Bettercap Wifi Auth Capture. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Input the number associated with the "Bettercap Recon" menu option and hit the enter key. If all goes well, your screen will appear as seen below. 

![A logo with a pixelated image](data:image/png;base64,)


Note: before continuing, make sure to run ```xhost si:localuser:root``` on your host machine to ensure xterm has permissions to open terminals windows at root. Revoke this access when finished with ```xhost -si:localuser:root```.

WifiForge uses xterm to allow interaction with the network. In the mininet-wifi CLI, type ```xterm a```. Similar to the image below, a xterm terminal window should appear.

![A screenshot of a computer](data:image/png;base64,)

Xterm's default font size is way too small. Make it bigger by holding \[Ctrl] and right click to view the preferences drop down. The text size can be adjusted as needed. 

![A screenshot of a computer](data:image/png;base64,)

It's that easy! No hardware required!

## Performing recon with Bettercap

With the lab environment setup, we can begin scanning for networks. Start by putting the wireless interface into monitor mode using ```airmon-ng start a-wlan0```. If airmon provides a prompt for automatic resolution, input ```y```and continue. Successful initialization will end with the message pictured below.

![A screenshot of a computer screen](data:image/png;base64,)


Confirm that a-wlan0mon is in monitor mode with ```ifconfig | grep flags```. a-wlan0mon should appear as a valid interface. 

![A screenshot of a computer](data:image/png;base64,)

Launch Bettercap using ```bettercap -iface a-wlan0mon```. Bettercap will greet you with a new prompt.

![A screen shot of a computer](data:image/png;base64,)

Too view valid commands, input ```help```. It's never a bad idea to read through the documentation!

![A screenshot of a computer program](data:image/png;base64,)

To view information specific to a module, input ```help <module name>```. This example primarily uses the wifi module. The output of ```help wifi``` can be seen below. 

![A screenshot of a computer screen](data:image/png;base64,)

Let's configure the console for a more convenient viewing experience. 

```
set wifi.show.sort clients desc 

set ticker.commands ‘clear; wifi.show’ 

ticker on 
```

```set wifi.show.sort clients desc``` - sort networks by number of connected clients
```set ticker.commands 'clear; wifi.show``` - Bettercap's ticker will periodically clear the screen and reload the wifi information panel, keeping the output clean.
```ticker on``` - activate the ticker.

After going through the above commands, you'll get the message seen below. 
![A blue and black sticker](data:image/png;base64,)

Let's get it running by enabling the module with ```wifi.recon on```.

It should not take long for networks to start appearing!

![A screenshot of a computer](data:image/png;base64,)

Each column displays different information about each network. 
- RSSI - the received signal strength indicator describes the strength of the signal relative to you.
- BSSID - the basic service set identifier is represented by the MAC address of the AP.
- SSID - the service set identifier is the name that clients see when connecting to the AP.
- Encryption - the type of encryption the network uses.
- WPS - Wifi protected setup is another security feature with it's own issues. Since all the rows are blank, none of our networks have WPS.
- Clients - How many clients Bettercap detected on the network. 
- Sent - How much data has been sent to the network.
- Received - How much data has been received from the network.
- Seen - when the network was first seen. 

Disable console logging using ```events.stream off```. Note that the monitor interface has not stopped channel hopping.

## Cracking handshakes!

Now that the nearby networks are known. We can crack their network keys using a deauth attack. First, a handshake between the client and the AP needs to be captured so the key can be cracked offline. This handshake can be quickly captured by kicking a client of the network, forcing it to reconnect.

Set the handshakes file using ```set wifi.handshakes.file ./loot/4whs```. The data we capture from the handshake will appear in this directory. 

Force the interface to operate only on the channel the WPA2 network exists on. In this case, lock to channel 6 using ```wifi.recon.channel 6```. Start the deauth attack using ```wifi.deauth <BSSID>```.

Bettercap notes how many handshakes are captured next to the packet count. Once one handshake is captured, kill the wifi module using ```wifi.recon off```.  Kill Bettercap using \[Ctrl] + c. 

The hashes can now be cracked using ```aircrack-ng -w ./rockyou.txt ./loot/4whs```. If prompted, select network noted as having a stored handshake. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Successful decryption of the network key should appear as pictured below. 

![A screenshot of a computer](data:image/png;base64,)

This lab demonstrates the ease with which WifiForge can provide a learning environment for learning wireless exploitation. Without WifiForge, repeating the steps outlined in this post would require a physical antenna and network. The environment in WifiForge is not limited to the attacks outlined in this post. Feel free to view other posts related to WifiForge or experiment using other attacks!
